<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 1:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I25526100630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>1.</label.designator><headtext>Introduction and History</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05a7682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>1:3.</label.designator><headtext>Order of presenting evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018073" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER611" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Ica1ada607fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 611(a)</cite.query> addresses the order of presenting evidence. <eos/><bos/>In federal practice, the courts are given discretion to exercise reasonable control over the presentation of testimony and evidence so as to reach the truth of the matter, make effective use of time, and protect witnesses from being harassed or unduly embarrassed. <eos/><bos/>The same is now true in Georgia.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic1299e407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The court has broad discretion in controlling the presentation of evidence. <eos/><bos/>In a case of first impression, <ital>Roberts v. State,</ital>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic129c5507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court held that the trial judge did not abuse his discretion in reopening the evidence and admitting new evidence upon request by the jury after commencement of deliberations.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018073" w-serial-number="1984141807" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ica1c88127fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Ellis v. Cameron &amp; Barkley Co.,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic129ec607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] the trial judge permitted the defendant to call his medical witness while the plaintiff was presenting his case-in-chief.<eos/><page no="3"/><page no="4"/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic1299e407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018073" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-611" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ica1b28807fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-611</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic129c5507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018073" w-serial-number="1981115741" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ica1b9db27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Roberts v. State, 247 Ga. 456, 277 S.E.2d 644 (1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic129ec607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018073" w-serial-number="1984141807" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ica1cd6327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Ellis v. Cameron &amp; Barkley Co., 171 Ga. App. 211, 319 S.E.2d 38 (1984)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="3"/><page no="4"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 1:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
